If you start with a square and we glue the opposite sides to one another, we get a torus (a surface in the shape of a donut). So we can think of this square as a torus, if we identify points on opposite sides. (For example, in some classic video games, walking off the right side of the screen makes you appear at the same height on the left side of the screen.)



For example, we can draw the 4-cycle C_4 using a square with opposite sides identified like so:



\begin{tikzpicture} %mathbook width=30%


\draw[gray, thick] (2,1.5) -!- (1.67,2.5);
\draw[gray, thick] (1,.5) -!- (1.67,-1.5);

\draw[gray, thick] (2,1.5) -!- (3,.5) -!- (2, -.5) -!- (1, .5);

\begin{scope}[shift={(2,.5)}]





\foreach \x in {0,1,2,3}
{
\draw[fill] (\x*90:1) circle (3pt);
}

\end{scope}


\draw[very thick, -latex] (0,2.5) -!- (4, 2.5);
\draw[very thick, -latex] (0,-1.5) -!- (4, -1.5);

\draw[very thick, color=red, -latex] (0,-1.5) -!- (0, 2.5);
\draw[very thick, color=red, -latex] (4,-1.5) -!- (4, 2.5);

\node at (2,-2.5) {$C_{4}$ on a torus};

\end{tikzpicture}






Using a square with opposite sides identified, show that you can draw both K_5 and K_{3,3} on a torus without any crossing edges!



\begin{tikzpicture} %mathbook width=90%



\begin{scope}[shift={(2,.5)}]






\foreach \x in {0,1,2,3,4}
{

\draw[fill] (\x*72+18:1) circle (3pt);


}

\end{scope}


\draw[very thick, -latex] (0,2.5) -!- (4, 2.5);
\draw[very thick, -latex] (0,-1.5) -!- (4, -1.5);

\draw[very thick, color=red, -latex] (0,-1.5) -!- (0, 2.5);
\draw[very thick, color=red, -latex] (4,-1.5) -!- (4, 2.5);

\node at (2,-2.5) {$K_{5}$ on a torus};


\begin{scope}[shift={(8,0)}]





\foreach \x in {1,2,3}
{

\draw[thick, fill=gray!50] (\x,0) circle (3pt);
\draw[fill] (\x,1) circle (3pt);
}


\draw[very thick, -latex] (0,2.5) -!- (4, 2.5);
\draw[very thick, -latex] (0,-1.5) -!- (4, -1.5);

\draw[very thick, color=red, -latex] (0,-1.5) -!- (0, 2.5);
\draw[very thick, color=red, -latex] (4,-1.5) -!- (4, 2.5);

\node at (2,-2.5) {$K_{3,3}$ on a torus};

\end{scope}


\end{tikzpicture}
